{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-01-09T00:58:21.631769+00:00", "modified": "2026-01-09T00:58:22.170597+00:00", "id": 18191661, "conceptrecid": "18191660", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18191661", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.18191660", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18191661", "metadata": {"title": "An investigation of the effects of conservation incentive programs on management of invasive species by private landowners", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18191661", "publication_date": "2019", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the IPBES Invasive Alien Species Assessment) Invasive species are a large and growing threat to biodiversity and ecosystem service provisioning globally as well as in southern Ontario, Canada's most biodiverse region. As in many other world regions, most land in southern Ontario is privately owned and therefore conservation programs that aim at private lands are important. Conservation incentive programs that target private lands are increasingly popular, but little is known about their effectiveness in achieving conservation objectives. To address this knowledge gap, we used a large survey of 1,200 Ontario landowners to investigate how successful conservation incentive programs are at motivating landowners to engage in invasive species management. Utilizing a quasiexperimental approach, we surveyed landowners participating in the Conservation Lands Tax Incentive Program (CLTIP), the Managed Forest Tax Incentive Program (MFTIP), or in both programs, as well as landowners who were program eligible but did not participate. Our results demonstrate the differential effects of participation in the two programs on specific landowner conservation behaviors: While participation in the MFTIP increased the likelihood of removing invasive species by a factor 2.5 and the planting of native species by a factor 4.3, participants in the CLTIP were no more likely to engage in these behaviors than landowners who did not participate in either program. We suggest that this behavioral disparity is due to the differences in the program designs: The CLTIP does not require a management plan, favors a short planning horizon, and mainly encourages passive management; in doing so it essentially breaks the causal chain that reinforces landowners' environmental awareness and a sense of responsibility for taking conservation actions. Our recommendations include requirements for impact evaluations of private land conservation incentive programs to ensure they achieve stated program outcomes, as well as conservation incentive program designs that oblige landowners to actively manage their land over longer time horizons.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Drescher, Michael", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Epstein, Graham B.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Warriner, G. Keith", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Rooney, Rebecca C.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Chapter 5", "biodiversity", "environment assessment", "IPBES", "Alien Invasive Species Assessment AIS", "invasive species"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/07b1990f19cb177bab0184a75aeeb606", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/a64854cfa6a5eb8d23eb6ae2186cfd8e96c4a7d4311578137748cf59a170446b", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/2352922/items/2T3CDEBG", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/2352922/items/2T3CDEBG", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/31383f8e993478c67533c7f2b97be725!/b51960-54077", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/359bd494433933b868f85e88d3437f76", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.1111/csp2.56", "relation": "isVariantFormOf", "resource_type": "publication", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.7430682", "relation": "isCitedBy", "resource_typ